Name: n-Heneicosane
Description: Henicosane is an alkane that has 21 carbons and a straight-chain structure. It has been isolated from plants like Periploca laevigata and Carthamus tinctorius. It has a role as a pheromone, a plant metabolite and a volatile oil component.

fish_seafood_concentrations.Value: Barnacle samples collected from five locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of heneicosane ranging from not detected to 2950 ng/g(1). Catfish samples collected from seven locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of octadecane ranging from <0.1 to 7.8 ng/g(2).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Hori T et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 83: 455-461 (2009)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SEDIMENTS: Heneicosane was detected in sediment samples from from 14 sites along the Shinano River in Japan, from Nov 2005 to April 2006 at concentrations ranging from less than 0.2 to 25 ng/g(1).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Rushdi AI et al; Arch Environ Contam Toxicol 49: 457-470 (2005)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SOIL: During winter 2002 soil and sand samples, from six locations in the Riyadh metropolitan area of Saudi Arabia, were examined for extractable organic matter; heneicosane was detected at relative concentrations between 0.05 to 0.69% (of total extractable organic matter) at five of six locations(1).
